.TH SLEEP(1),User Commands,SLEEP(1)

.SH NAME
sleep - suspend execution for a given interval

.SH SYNOPSIS
sleep interval

.SH DESCRIPTION
sleep suspends the current process until the system clock reaches a target time equal to the current time plus interval.

interval is either a plain number of seconds, or a sequence of value-unit pairs such as 1h30m or 2m15s500j.
Recognised units are:

h: hours

m: minutes

s: seconds

j: jiffies (1/60 of a second)

Each numeric component must be less than the natural limit for its unit (s and m below 60, h below 24, j below 60).
The pairs may appear in any order and may be repeated;
their values are summed.

sleep yields the CPU to other processes while waiting.

.SH EXAMPLES
sleep 5

Wait five seconds.

sleep 1h30m

Wait one and a half hours.

sleep 200j

Wait 200 jiffies (about 3.3 seconds).

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
sleep: missing operand - no interval was given.

sleep: invalid time interval 'ARG' - the argument could not be parsed, contained an unknown unit, or a component was out of range.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: Interval elapsed.

1: Missing operand or invalid interval.

.SH SEE ALSO
date(1), time(1)
